{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:08:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:08:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"332"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/332"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.09,0.05,0.12,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"332"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54577"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/332"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"332"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40085"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15555"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54577"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents with a six-month history of worsening nocturia, now getting up twice at night to pass urine. He was previously healthy without any significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing a thorough workup including biopsy of his prostate, he is diagnosed with carcinoma of the prostate. Investigations showed a small volume T2 cancer with Gleason score 3+4=7. PSA value was measured at 7 ng/mL (\u2264 10 ng/ml). There was no evidence of any metastatic spread.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radical prostatectomy","Watchful waiting","Chemoradiotherapy","Androgen suppression therapy","Active surveillance"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate treatment of a patient\u0027s prostate cancer is based on a number of factors concerning both the lesion itself and patient\u0027s overall health. In this case of a fit, relatively young man, the current evidence recommends \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical prostatectomy\u003C/strong\u003E in low risk patients with life expectancies exceeding 10 years. This patient is considered low risk due to the size, grade and lack of metastasis of the cancer while absence of significant medical history points towards a good life expectancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWatchful waiting is an appropriate form of management for patients with low life expectancies where the potential harms and effect on quality of life of interventions outweigh the mortality benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChemoradiotherapy would only be considered if he had metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAndrogen suppression therapy (also known as androgen deprivation therapy) is used in patients with metastatic disease or in combination with radiotherapy for patients with locally advanced disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive surveillance is used when a small volume and low grade cancer is found, and is thought to be clinically insignificant. By monitoring these cancers, treatment can be avoided or delayed, and therefore side effects of treatment are avoided. While this is an option, it is less ideal than surgery in young men.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Surgical intervention is indicated for low-risk prostate cancers in patients with good life expectancy (\u226510 years)."],"references":["1. Scherr D, Swindle P, Scardino P. National Comprehensive Cancer Network guidelines for the management of prostate cancer. Urology. 2003;61(2):14-24.","Bill-Axelson A, Holmberg L, Garmo H, et al. Radical Prostatectomy or Watchful Waiting in Prostate Cancer \u2014 29-Year Follow-up. N Engl J Med 2018; 379:2319-29.","Graham J, Kirkbride P, Cann K, et al. Prostate cancer: summary of updated NICE guidance. BMJ 2013;348:f7524"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40085"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"332"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40085"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-07T21:37:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-07T21:38:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"332"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54577"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":